        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Sensitivity:
We need to detect small differences in the methanol emission distribution in the three Serpens cores. This requires a 3 sigma level of 10 mJy/beam (see Figure 2 in the proposal) in 1 km/s channels, or 3 mJy/beam rms. We choose to observe at higher spectral resolution and rebin the data ourselves. In this way, we will be able to follow the methanol gas dynamics in the regions where the S/N permits it. 

Imaging requirements:
In order to distinguish between the different desorption models, we require a minimum linear resolution of 500 AU, or 1" at the distance of Serpens (415 pc). The largest spatial structures in each pointing will be the envelopes themselves, and since emission is smoothly distributed over the envelopes, these are our largest spatial scales. Typical envelope radii are of the order of 5000 AU, 25" diameter. We therefore request that these observations be carried out including the ACA + TP. 

We note that to distinguish between the different desorption scenarios, we mainly require good image fidelity in the inner 10" of each envelope (Fig. 2) and therefore it is not necessary to obtain mosaic observations. 

Spectral requirements:
We have placed two basebands in the lower sideband such that they cover five CH3OH 2-1 transitions (see Table 1). One baseband is placed on C18O 1-0, allowing us to follow the cold CO structure in conjunction with the CH3OH structure. 

Data rate:
Using three basebands results in a high data rate (&gt; 12 MB/s), but this is absolutely required in order for us to achieve our science goals. If one baseband is dropped, we will loose several methanol lines, or the C18O line, neither of which is acceptable. </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
