    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Outside of the methanol snow line, the CH3OH ice reservoir is connected to the CH3OH gas by different non-thermal processes. The efficiencies of most of these processes are poorly constrained and therefore so is our ability to infer the size of the methanol reservoir during most stages of star and planet formation. We propose to exploit the expectation that different non-thermal desorption pathways result in dramatically different methanol gas distributions as a function of extinction and temperature to test which desorption mechanism dominates the delivery of methanol into the gas-phase during low-mass star formation. We propose to do this in the Serpens core, which is a unique laboratory for this kind of study because of: 1. a well-constrained temperature and density structure, and 2. the existence of ice maps in this line of sight, which will enable us to infer both the dominating desorption mechanism *and* put observational constrains on its efficiency under different environmental conditions.</prp:abstract>
